    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener><salute>Dear Sir</salute></opener>
                <p>I did not understand till a very short time since, that I was oblig’d to You for
                    two Prints which you was kind enough to leave at <persName ref="pe0320">Bretherton</persName>’s for me. I desire to give you my best thanks for them, and to
                    assure you that I think myself very much honor’d in having a place in your
                    remembrance. I have built a House in <placeName ref="pl0759">Stratton
                        Street</placeName> <placeName ref="pl2035">Picadilly</placeName>,<note type="editorial"><persName ref="pe0313">Richard Bull</persName>'s house in town was
                            <placeName ref="pl0759">no. 10 Stratton Street</placeName>.
                        Evans, ‘Richard Bull and Thomas Pennant’, 271. The earliest letter from
                            <persName ref="pe0232">Pennant</persName> addressed to
                            <persName ref="pe0313">Bull</persName> there is dated 20 April 1780 (<ref target="1005.xml">1005</ref>).</note> and if business or amusement
                    should call you to <placeName ref="pl0699">London</placeName> next
                    winter, I should have a real pleasure in seeing you there, because you always
                    amuse and inform me, &amp; I have besides some few things, which I wish to ask
                    your opinion of.</p>
                <closer><salute>I am Dear Sir<lb/> Yours very much</salute><signed><persName ref="pe0313">Rich<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>:
                        Bull</persName></signed>
                    <dateline><placeName ref="pl0757">Watcombe Place</placeName><lb/>
                        <placeName ref="pl1073">Southampton</placeName><lb/> 28 June 1778</dateline></closer>
            </div>
        </body>
